# Key Findings

- **H. pylori inversely associated with erosive reflux disease (ERD)** — H. pylori prevalence was lowest in ERD patients (5.2%) compared to NERD and functional dyspepsia, supporting the hypothesis that H. pylori may be protective against erosive esophageal damage ([[sugihartono-2022-gastric-microbiota-h-pylori-gerd|cross-sectional, n=197]])
- **[[anaerobacillus]] found exclusively in ERD patients** — a novel finding suggesting this genus as a potential biomarker for erosive disease
- **ERD had significantly higher alpha diversity than NERD** — counterintuitively, the more severe phenotype harbored a more diverse gastric microbial community
- **[[streptococcus]], [[rothia]], and [[alloprevotella]]** were among the dominant gastric genera across all GERD subtypes

# Relevance to WikiBiome

- Informs [[helicobacter-pylori]] entity page — adds evidence for the protective role of H. pylori in GERD, contributing to the nuanced view of H. pylori as both pathogen and commensal
- Informs [[alloprevotella]] and [[rothia]] entity pages as components of the gastric microbiome in GERD
- The inverse H. pylori-GERD relationship challenges simplistic "eradicate all pathogens" narratives
- Higher diversity in ERD vs. NERD challenges the assumption that more severe disease always means lower diversity

# Relevance to Cureva

- **Primitive 4 (Microbial Metal Dependencies as Achilles' Heels)**: [[helicobacter-pylori]] is a [[nickel]]-dependent organism (urease, NiFe-hydrogenase) — its absence in ERD may reflect altered nickel ecology in the erosive esophageal environment
- The protective role of H. pylori in GERD has implications for STOP pages — H. pylori eradication in GERD patients may be counterproductive if the organism is serving a protective ecological function
- Anaerobacillus as an ERD-exclusive genus warrants investigation as a biomarker for disease severity stratification
